entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued October 12 at 4:38AM EDT by NWS Albany NY
entry.summary:
Fine fuels remain very dry across southern Vermont according to the Vermont Department of Forests, Parks and Recreation. While minimum relative humidity values will only be 55 to 75 percent, gusty easterly winds up to 20 to 30 mph may have an impact on fire weather conditions today. If any fires were to start the weather and fuel conditions could cause fires to quickly get out of control and be difficult to contain. Furthermore, breezy conditions will continue this evening into Monday, however, forecast rainfall is expected to mitigate any further fire weather concerns.
For more information about the current fire danger rating, any burn restrictions, and wildfire prevention and education, please visit your state forestry or environmental protection website. Remember, a debris burn ban is in effect for all of Vermont which means no open burning of debris is allowed.

entry.title: Coastal Flood Warning issued October 12 at 4:33AM EDT until October 12 at 6:00PM EDT by NWS Wakefield VA
entry.summary:
* WHAT...For the High Surf Advisory, large breaking waves of 10 to 15 feet expected in the surf zone. For the Coastal Flood Warning, 2 to 3 feet of inundation above ground level expected in low-lying areas near shorelines and tidal waterways.
* WHERE...Eastern Currituck County.
* WHEN...For the Coastal Flood Warning, until 6 PM EDT this evening. For the High Surf Advisory, until 4 PM EDT Monday.
* IMPACTS...Moderate to major flooding will cause extensive inundation and flooding of numerous roads and buildings resulting in a significant threat to property and life. Water will be 2 to 3 feet or more above ground level in some areas. Severe flooding will extend inland from the waterfront and shoreline flooding homes, businesses and isolating some neighborhoods. Numerous roads will be impassable under several feet of water and cars submerged. Some areas may need to be evacuated. Erosion and damage to dune structures will be possible. Actions should be taken to protect property along the immediate shoreline.
* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Peak water levels are expected with the high tide cycle occurring this afternoon, but at least minor flooding is expected into early Monday morning.

entry.title: High Wind Watch issued October 11 at 11:51AM MDT until October 13 at 12:00PM MDT by NWS Missoula MT
entry.summary:
* WHAT...Northeast winds 25 to 45 mph with gusts up to 55 mph possible. Across the southern parts of Flathead Lake, waves between 3 and 5 feet.
* WHERE...Eastern Flathead Valley between Lake Blaine and Swan Lake, and Highway 35 south of Wood's Bay to Finley Point on the east side of Flathead Lake.
* WHEN...From Sunday evening through Monday morning.
* IMPACTS...Damaging winds could blow down trees and power lines. Widespread power outages are possible in the areas listed. Boat docks on the southwest side of Flathead Lake could be damaged. Travel could be difficult, especially for high profile vehicles.
* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Since Flathead Lake is around two feet below full pool, boat docks will be susceptible to damage due to the strong winds and choppy waves.
There is a low probability of a high impact situation where enough wet snow could fall on the higher spots of U.S. 93, northwest of Polson, and produce patchy slick spots and/or power outages Sunday evening.

entry.title: Air Quality Alert issued October 11 at 12:43PM CDT by NWS Houston/Galveston TX
entry.summary:
AQAHGX
The Texas Commission on Environmental Quality (TCEQ) has issued an Ozone Action Day for the Houston, Galveston, and Brazoria area for Sunday, October 12, 2025.
Atmospheric conditions are expected to be favorable for producing high levels of ozone pollution in the Houston, Galveston, and surrounding areas on Sunday. You can help prevent ozone pollution by sharing a ride, walking, riding a bicycle, taking your lunch to work, avoiding drive through lanes, conserving energy and keeping your vehicle properly tuned.

entry.title: Air Quality Alert issued October 10 at 12:01PM PDT by NWS Spokane WA
entry.summary:
An Air Quality Alert has been issued by the Washington Department of Ecology
An Air Quality Alert has been issued by the Washington Department of Ecology for Chelan and Douglas Counties, effective immediately until further notice due to current and expected wildfire smoke from regional wildfires. Smoke impacts will be concentrated in the Wenatchee River Corridor (including the Cashmere, Wenatchee, East Wenatchee, and Rock Island communities). Air quality in the rest of Chelan and Douglas Counties is expected to remain good to moderate. When air quality is unhealthy, everyone should reduce exposure. Limit time outside, avoid strenuous activity, and follow tips for cleaner indoor air.
